data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, you could modernize this to use `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner concurrency:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you thread-pool management, better scalability, and cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
